5// Declares a Simulator for S390 instructions if we are not generating a native
6// S390 binary. This Simulator allows us to run and debug S390 code generation
7// on regular desktop machines.
8// V8 calls into generated code via the GeneratedCode wrapper,
9// which will start execution in the Simulator or forwards to the real entry
10// on a S390 hardware platform.
11

30class CachePage {
31 public:
32 static const int LINE_VALID = 0;
33 static const int LINE_INVALID = 1;
34
35 static const int kPageShift = 12;
36 static const int kPageSize = 1 << kPageShift;
37 static const int kPageMask = kPageSize - 1;
38 static const int kLineShift = 2; // The cache line is only 4 bytes right now.
39 static const int kLineLength = 1 << kLineShift;
40 static const int kLineMask = kLineLength - 1;
41
42 CachePage() { memset(&validity_map_, LINE_INVALID, sizeof(validity_map_)); }
43
44 char* ValidityByte(int offset) {
45 return &validity_map_[offset >> kLineShift];
46 }
47
48 char* CachedData(int offset) { return &data_[offset]; }
49
50 private:
51 char data_[kPageSize]; // The cached data.
52 static const int kValidityMapSize = kPageSize >> kLineShift;
53 char validity_map_[kValidityMapSize]; // One byte per line.
54};

56template <class T>
57static T ComputeRounding(T a, int mode) {
58 switch (mode) {
59 case ROUND_TO_NEAREST_AWAY_FROM_0:
60 return std::round(a);
61 case ROUND_TO_NEAREST_TO_EVEN:
62 return std::nearbyint(a);
63 case ROUND_TOWARD_0:
64 return std::trunc(a);
65 case ROUND_TOWARD_POS_INF:
66 return std::ceil(a);
67 case ROUND_TOWARD_NEG_INF:
68 return std::floor(a);
69 default:
70 UNIMPLEMENTED();
71 }
72 return 0;
73}

141 // Unlike Integer values, Floating Point values are located on the left most
142 // side of a native 64 bit register. As FP registers are a subset of vector
143 // registers, 64 and 32 bit FP values need to be located on first lane (lane
144 // number 0) of a vector register.
145 template <class T>
146 T get_fpr(int dreg) {
147 DCHECK(dreg >= 0 && dreg < kNumFPRs);
148 return get_simd_register_by_lane<T>(dreg, 0);
149 }
150
151 template <class T>
152 void set_fpr(int dreg, const T val) {
153 DCHECK(dreg >= 0 && dreg < kNumFPRs);
154 set_simd_register_by_lane<T>(dreg, 0, val);
155 }

273 template <typename T>
274 void SetS390ConditionCode(T lhs, T rhs) {
275 condition_reg_ = 0;
276 if (lhs == rhs) {
277 condition_reg_ |= CC_EQ;
278 } else if (lhs < rhs) {
279 condition_reg_ |= CC_LT;
280 } else if (lhs > rhs) {
281 condition_reg_ |= CC_GT;
282 }
283
284 // We get down here only for floating point
285 // comparisons and the values are unordered
286 // i.e. NaN
287 if (condition_reg_ == 0) condition_reg_ = unordered;
288 }
289
290 // Used by arithmetic operations that use carry.
291 template <typename T>
292 void SetS390ConditionCodeCarry(T result, bool overflow) {
293 condition_reg_ = 0;
294 bool zero_result = (result == static_cast<T>(0));
295 if (zero_result && !overflow) {
296 condition_reg_ |= 8;
297 } else if (!zero_result && !overflow) {
298 condition_reg_ |= 4;
299 } else if (zero_result && overflow) {
300 condition_reg_ |= 2;
301 } else if (!zero_result && overflow) {
302 condition_reg_ |= 1;
303 }
304 if (condition_reg_ == 0) UNREACHABLE();
305 }
306
307 bool isNaN(double value) { return (value != value); }
308
309 // Set the condition code for bitwise operations
310 // CC0 is set if value == 0.
311 // CC1 is set if value != 0.
312 // CC2/CC3 are not set.
313 template <typename T>
314 void SetS390BitWiseConditionCode(T value) {
315 condition_reg_ = 0;
316
317 if (value == 0)
318 condition_reg_ |= CC_EQ;
319 else
320 condition_reg_ |= CC_LT;
321 }
322
323 void SetS390OverflowCode(bool isOF) {
324 if (isOF) condition_reg_ = CC_OF;
325 }
326
327 bool TestConditionCode(Condition mask) {
328 // Check for unconditional branch
329 if (mask == 0xf) return true;
330
331 return (condition_reg_ & mask) != 0;
332 }

352 // Architecture state.
353 // On z9 and higher and supported Linux on z Systems platforms, all registers
354 // are 64-bit, even in 31-bit mode.
355 uint64_t registers_[kNumGPRs];
356 union fpr_t {
357 int8_t int8[16];
358 uint8_t uint8[16];
359 int16_t int16[8];
360 uint16_t uint16[8];
361 int32_t int32[4];
362 uint32_t uint32[4];
363 int64_t int64[2];
364 uint64_t uint64[2];
365 float f32[4];
366 double f64[2];
367 };
368 fpr_t fp_registers_[kNumFPRs];
369
370 static constexpr fpr_t fp_zero = {{0}};
371
372 fpr_t get_simd_register(int reg) { return fp_registers_[reg]; }
373
374 void set_simd_register(int reg, const fpr_t& value) {
375 fp_registers_[reg] = value;
376 }
377
378 // Vector register lane numbers on IBM machines are reversed compared to
379 // x64. For example, doing an I32x4 extract_lane with lane number 0 on x64
380 // will be equal to lane number 3 on IBM machines. Vector registers are only
381 // used for compiling Wasm code at the moment. Wasm is also little endian
382 // enforced. On s390 native, we manually do a reverse byte whenever values are
383 // loaded/stored from memory to a Simd register. On the simulator however, we
384 // do not reverse the bytes and data is just copied as is from one memory
385 // location to another location which represents a register. To keep the Wasm
386 // simulation accurate, we need to make sure accessing a lane is correctly
387 // simulated and as such we reverse the lane number on the getters and setters
388 // below. We need to be careful when getting/setting values on the Low or High
389 // side of a simulated register. In the simulation, "Low" is equal to the MSB
390 // and "High" is equal to the LSB on memory. "force_ibm_lane_numbering" could
391 // be used to disabled automatic lane number reversal and help with accessing
392 // the Low or High side of a simulated register.
393 template <class T>
394 T get_simd_register_by_lane(int reg, int lane,
395 bool force_ibm_lane_numbering = true) {
396 if (force_ibm_lane_numbering) {
397 lane = (kSimd128Size / sizeof(T)) - 1 - lane;
398 }
399 CHECK_LE(lane, kSimd128Size / sizeof(T));
400 CHECK_LT(reg, kNumFPRs);
401 CHECK_GE(lane, 0);
402 CHECK_GE(reg, 0);
403 return (reinterpret_cast<T*>(&fp_registers_[reg]))[lane];
404 }
405
406 template <class T>
407 void set_simd_register_by_lane(int reg, int lane, const T& value,
408 bool force_ibm_lane_numbering = true) {
409 if (force_ibm_lane_numbering) {
410 lane = (kSimd128Size / sizeof(T)) - 1 - lane;
411 }
412 CHECK_LE(lane, kSimd128Size / sizeof(T));
413 CHECK_LT(reg, kNumFPRs);
414 CHECK_GE(lane, 0);
415 CHECK_GE(reg, 0);
416 (reinterpret_cast<T*>(&fp_registers_[reg]))[lane] = value;
417 }

426 static const size_t kStackProtectionSize = 256 * kSystemPointerSize;
427 // This includes a protection margin at each end of the stack area.
428 static size_t AllocatedStackSize() {
429#if V8_TARGET_ARCH_S390X
430 size_t stack_size = v8_flags.sim_stack_size * KB;
431#else
432 size_t stack_size = MB; // allocate 1MB for stack
433#endif
434 return stack_size + (2 * kStackProtectionSize);
435 }
436 static size_t UsableStackSize() {
437 return AllocatedStackSize() - kStackProtectionSize;
